{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VzmyxdZ9CQ9fa3jEoLmhS7","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"next-auth v5 nextjs 16 app router 2026 installation\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Migrating to v5\",\"url\":\"https://authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5\"},{\"title\":\"App Router: Adding Authentication | Next.js\",\"url\":\"https://nextjs.org/learn/dashboard-app/adding-authentication\"},{\"title\":\"Stop Crying Over Auth: A Senior Dev’s Guide to Next.js 16 & Auth.js v5 | by Nesan | JavaScript in Plain English\",\"url\":\"https://javascript.plainenglish.io/stop-crying-over-auth-a-senior-devs-guide-to-next-js-15-auth-js-v5-42a57bc5b4ce\"},{\"title\":\"Getting Started: Installation | Next.js\",\"url\":\"https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation\"},{\"title\":\"Installation/compatibility issue: NextAuth with Next.js 16 · Issue #13302 · nextauthjs/next-auth\",\"url\":\"https://github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302\"},{\"title\":\"How to setup NextAuth v5 on the Next.js frontend with App Router and custom forms | by Kamil Matejuk | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@kamilmatejuk/how-to-setup-nextauth-v5-on-the-next-js-frontend-with-app-router-and-custom-forms-2ac408ba973d\"},{\"title\":\"Getting Started | NextAuth.js\",\"url\":\"https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/example\"},{\"title\":\"Next.js Docs: App Router | Next.js\",\"url\":\"https://nextjs.org/docs/app\"},{\"title\":\"Complete Authentication Guide for Next.js App Router in 2025\",\"url\":\"https://clerk.com/articles/complete-authentication-guide-for-nextjs-app-router\"},{\"title\":\"Auth.js | Installation\",\"url\":\"https://authjs.dev/getting-started/installation\"}]\n\nHere's a summary of the latest information on **NextAuth (Auth.js) v5** installation with **Next.js 16** and the **App Router**:\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nNextAuth is transforming into Auth.js. For Next.js 16, you should use v5, which is currently in beta/RC but stable enough for production use.\n\nNextAuth.js version 5 is a major rewrite of the `next-auth` package, but it introduces as few breaking changes as possible.\n\n---\n\n## Installation\n\nInstall NextAuth.js by running the install command in your terminal — the beta version of NextAuth.js is compatible with Next.js 14+.\n\nYou would typically install it with:\n\n```bash\nnpm install next-auth@beta\n```\n\n### Known Compatibility Issue with Next.js 16\n\nThere is a known issue that blocks installation unless using `--legacy-peer-deps` or `--force`. The documentation is unclear whether NextAuth v5+ is intended to support Next.js 16 out of the box. Specifically:\n\n- The NextAuth v5 `peerDependency` range may need to be updated for Next.js 16.\n- There may be new migration or configuration steps specific to Next.js 16.\n\nSo if you encounter peer dependency errors, you can work around them with:\n\n```bash\nnpm install next-auth@beta --legacy-peer-deps\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Configuration Changes for Next.js 16\n\n### `middleware.ts` → `proxy.ts`\n\nAs of Next.js 16, `middleware.ts` has been renamed to `proxy.ts`. If you are using an older version of Next.js, use `middleware.ts` with `export { auth as middleware }` instead.\n\n### Root Configuration File\n\nOne of the goals was to avoid exporting your configuration from one file and passing it around as `authOptions` throughout your application. The configuration file is now moved to the root of the repository and exports the necessary functions (`auth`, `signIn`, `signOut`, `handlers`, etc.).\n\nFor example, create an `auth.ts` file at the project root:\n\n```ts\n// auth.ts\nimport NextAuth from 'next-auth'\n\nexport const { auth, handlers, signIn, signOut } = NextAuth({\n  providers: [/* your providers */],\n})\n```\n\nYou can also create an `auth.config.ts` file at the root of your project that exports an `authConfig` object with configuration options for NextAuth.js, including the `pages` option for custom sign-in routes.\n\n---\n\n## Next.js 16 App Router\n\nNext.js is currently at version 16.1.6, and the App Router is a file-system based router that uses React's latest features such as Server Components, Suspense, and Server Functions.\n\nNextAuth.js v5's complete rewrite prioritizes App Router compatibility with a universal `auth()` function working across all Next.js contexts. The edge-first design ensures compatibility with Vercel Edge Runtime and Cloudflare Workers.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Start Steps\n\n1. **Create a Next.js 16 project** using `create-next-app` (select App Router).\n2. **Install NextAuth v5**: `npm install next-auth@beta` (use `--legacy-peer-deps` if needed).\n3. **Generate an `AUTH_SECRET`**: `npx auth secret` or `openssl rand -base64 33`.\n4. **Create `auth.ts`** at the project root to export `auth`, `handlers`, `signIn`, and `signOut`.\n5. **Create `app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`** and wire up the handlers.\n6. **Create `proxy.ts`** (not `middleware.ts`) for route protection in Next.js 16.\n7. **Set environment variables** (`AUTH_SECRET`, provider credentials, etc.).\n\n---\n\n## Useful Resources\n\n- **Official Auth.js installation guide**: [authjs.dev/getting-started/installation](https://authjs.dev/getting-started/installation)\n- **Migration to v5 guide**: [authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5](https://authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5)\n- **Next.js 16 installation docs**: [nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation)\n- **GitHub issue on Next.js 16 compatibility**: [github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302](https://github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302)\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c220b3b-cbe4-4615-939a-f8ccaabf4974","uuid":"48a7bdde-37bf-4e73-ad20-4e224e1c2233","tool_use_result":{"query":"next-auth v5 nextjs 16 app router 2026 installation","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01Tyi7qLn62kyYq3VuxSbQg8","content":[{"title":"Migrating to v5","url":"https://authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5"},{"title":"App Router: Adding Authentication | Next.js","url":"https://nextjs.org/learn/dashboard-app/adding-authentication"},{"title":"Stop Crying Over Auth: A Senior Dev’s Guide to Next.js 16 & Auth.js v5 | by Nesan | JavaScript in Plain English","url":"https://javascript.plainenglish.io/stop-crying-over-auth-a-senior-devs-guide-to-next-js-15-auth-js-v5-42a57bc5b4ce"},{"title":"Getting Started: Installation | Next.js","url":"https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation"},{"title":"Installation/compatibility issue: NextAuth with Next.js 16 · Issue #13302 · nextauthjs/next-auth","url":"https://github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302"},{"title":"How to setup NextAuth v5 on the Next.js frontend with App Router and custom forms | by Kamil Matejuk | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@kamilmatejuk/how-to-setup-nextauth-v5-on-the-next-js-frontend-with-app-router-and-custom-forms-2ac408ba973d"},{"title":"Getting Started | NextAuth.js","url":"https://next-auth.js.org/getting-started/example"},{"title":"Next.js Docs: App Router | Next.js","url":"https://nextjs.org/docs/app"},{"title":"Complete Authentication Guide for Next.js App Router in 2025","url":"https://clerk.com/articles/complete-authentication-guide-for-nextjs-app-router"},{"title":"Auth.js | Installation","url":"https://authjs.dev/getting-started/installation"}]},"Here's a summary of the latest information on **NextAuth (Auth.js) v5** installation with **Next.js 16** and the **App Router**:\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nNextAuth is transforming into Auth.js. For Next.js 16, you should use v5, which is currently in beta/RC but stable enough for production use.\n\nNextAuth.js version 5 is a major rewrite of the `next-auth` package, but it introduces as few breaking changes as possible.\n\n---\n\n## Installation\n\nInstall NextAuth.js by running the install command in your terminal — the beta version of NextAuth.js is compatible with Next.js 14+.\n\nYou would typically install it with:\n\n```bash\nnpm install next-auth@beta\n```\n\n### Known Compatibility Issue with Next.js 16\n\nThere is a known issue that blocks installation unless using `--legacy-peer-deps` or `--force`. The documentation is unclear whether NextAuth v5+ is intended to support Next.js 16 out of the box. Specifically:\n\n- The NextAuth v5 `peerDependency` range may need to be updated for Next.js 16.\n- There may be new migration or configuration steps specific to Next.js 16.\n\nSo if you encounter peer dependency errors, you can work around them with:\n\n```bash\nnpm install next-auth@beta --legacy-peer-deps\n```\n\n---\n\n## Key Configuration Changes for Next.js 16\n\n### `middleware.ts` → `proxy.ts`\n\nAs of Next.js 16, `middleware.ts` has been renamed to `proxy.ts`. If you are using an older version of Next.js, use `middleware.ts` with `export { auth as middleware }` instead.\n\n### Root Configuration File\n\nOne of the goals was to avoid exporting your configuration from one file and passing it around as `authOptions` throughout your application. The configuration file is now moved to the root of the repository and exports the necessary functions (`auth`, `signIn`, `signOut`, `handlers`, etc.).\n\nFor example, create an `auth.ts` file at the project root:\n\n```ts\n// auth.ts\nimport NextAuth from 'next-auth'\n\nexport const { auth, handlers, signIn, signOut } = NextAuth({\n  providers: [/* your providers */],\n})\n```\n\nYou can also create an `auth.config.ts` file at the root of your project that exports an `authConfig` object with configuration options for NextAuth.js, including the `pages` option for custom sign-in routes.\n\n---\n\n## Next.js 16 App Router\n\nNext.js is currently at version 16.1.6, and the App Router is a file-system based router that uses React's latest features such as Server Components, Suspense, and Server Functions.\n\nNextAuth.js v5's complete rewrite prioritizes App Router compatibility with a universal `auth()` function working across all Next.js contexts. The edge-first design ensures compatibility with Vercel Edge Runtime and Cloudflare Workers.\n\n---\n\n## Quick Start Steps\n\n1. **Create a Next.js 16 project** using `create-next-app` (select App Router).\n2. **Install NextAuth v5**: `npm install next-auth@beta` (use `--legacy-peer-deps` if needed).\n3. **Generate an `AUTH_SECRET`**: `npx auth secret` or `openssl rand -base64 33`.\n4. **Create `auth.ts`** at the project root to export `auth`, `handlers`, `signIn`, and `signOut`.\n5. **Create `app/api/auth/[...nextauth]/route.ts`** and wire up the handlers.\n6. **Create `proxy.ts`** (not `middleware.ts`) for route protection in Next.js 16.\n7. **Set environment variables** (`AUTH_SECRET`, provider credentials, etc.).\n\n---\n\n## Useful Resources\n\n- **Official Auth.js installation guide**: [authjs.dev/getting-started/installation](https://authjs.dev/getting-started/installation)\n- **Migration to v5 guide**: [authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5](https://authjs.dev/getting-started/migrating-to-v5)\n- **Next.js 16 installation docs**: [nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/getting-started/installation)\n- **GitHub issue on Next.js 16 compatibility**: [github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302](https://github.com/nextauthjs/next-auth/issues/13302)"],"durationSeconds":28.178608207999996}}
